data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction is no longer needed. Replace with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**Same-named properties across complex types** are now uniquified (e.g., `Street` → `Street1`). **Nested complex types** use the full path (`Complex_NestedComplex_Property` instead of `NestedComplex_Property`).

Both generate rename migrations. Pin the old names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a => {
        a.Property(addr => addr.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a => {
        a.Property(addr => addr.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested: Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p => {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, a => {
            a.Property(addr => addr.City)
             .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City"); // preserves old name
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gains a `string logCommandText` parameter (redacted SQL for safe logging):

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
    DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)   // ← add this
{ /* logging — use logCommandText for safe output */ }
```

Update all method signatures in your implementation to match.
